  "text": "## Kubernetes Scheduler Plugin Framework Architecture\n\n### Overview\nThe Kubernetes scheduler plugin framework is a pluggable architecture that orchestrates scheduling decisions through multiple extension points. Here is the mapping of key components:\n\n### 1. Framework Interface Definitions (pkg/scheduler/framework/interface.go)\n\nThe core plugin interfaces are defined in `pkg/scheduler/framework/interface.go`:\n\n**Parent Interface:**\n- `Plugin` (line 443): Parent type for all scheduling framework plugins, requiring a `Name()` method\n\n**Extension Point Plugins:**\n- `PreEnqueuePlugin` (line 452): Plugins called before adding pods to activeQ\n- `QueueSortPlugin` (line 464): Plugins for sorting pods in the scheduling queue\n- `PreFilterPlugin` (line 512): Plugins called at the beginning of the scheduling cycle to filter resources\n- `FilterPlugin` (line 540): Plugins that filter out hosts that cannot run a pod\n- `PostFilterPlugin` (line 561): Plugins called when scheduling fails, can implement preemption\n- `PreScorePlugin` (line 587): Informational plugins called after filtering phase\n- `ScorePlugin` (line 607): Plugins that rank filtered nodes\n- `ReservePlugin` (line 624): Plugins that reserve resources or update plugin state\n- `PreBindPlugin` (line 640): Plugins called before binding a pod\n- `PermitPlugin` (line 660): Plugins that control when binding occurs\n- `BindPlugin` (line 673): Plugins that bind a pod to a node\n- `PostBindPlugin` (line 649): Plugins called after a pod is bound\n\n**Framework Interface:**\n- `Framework` (line 686): Main interface managing all plugins and orchestrating scheduling cycles\n- `Handle` (line 783): Interface providing data and tools that plugins can use\n\n### 2. ScheduleOne Orchestration Function (pkg/scheduler/schedule_one.go)\n\n- `ScheduleOne()` method (line 65): Main function that drives the entire scheduling workflow for a single pod. It:\n  - Retrieves the next pod from the scheduling queue\n  - Determines which framework profile to use\n  - Orchestrates the full scheduling cycle including filtering, scoring, and binding phases\n\n### 3. Scheduler Top-Level Struct (pkg/scheduler/scheduler.go)\n\n- `Scheduler` struct (line 66): Top-level scheduler component that:\n  - Manages the scheduling queue (SchedulingQueue field)\n  - Holds the cache and profiles (Profiles field)\n  - Has a `NextPod` callback to get pods from the queue\n  - Has FailureHandler and SchedulePod callbacks\n\n- `Scheduler.Run()` method (line 464): Entry point that:\n  - Starts the scheduling queue\n  - Spawns a goroutine running `ScheduleOne` in a loop\n  - Handles graceful shutdown of the scheduler\n\n### 4. frameworkImpl Runtime (pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/framework.go)\n\n- `frameworkImpl` struct (line 52): The component responsible for initializing and running plugins. It contains:\n  - Registry of available plugins\n  - Slices of plugin implementations for each extension point (preFilterPlugins, filterPlugins, scorePlugins, etc.)\n  - Metrics recording\n  - Event handling\n\n- `RunFilterPlugins()` method (line 872): Runs all configured filter plugins for a pod on a node. Returns non-success status if any filter rejects the pod.\n\n- `RunScorePlugins()` method (line 1112): Runs all score plugins in parallel:\n  - Calls each plugin's Score method for each node\n  - Runs NormalizeScore extensions\n  - Computes weighted scores from all plugins\n  - Returns NodePluginScores with combined scores\n\n- `RunFilterPluginsWithNominatedPods()` method (line 984): Variant that considers nominated pods when filtering, called during preemption evaluation.\n\n### 5. Plugin Registry (pkg/scheduler/framework/plugins/registry.go)\n\n- `NewInTreeRegistry()` function (line 47): Builds and returns the registry containing all built-in plugins:\n  - DynamicResources\n  - ImageLocality\n  - TaintToleration\n  - NodeName\n  - NodePorts\n  - NodeAffinity\n  - PodTopologySpread\n  - NodeUnschedulable\n  - NodeResources (Fit and BalancedAllocation)\n  - VolumeBinding\n  - VolumeRestrictions\n  - VolumeZone\n  - NodeVolumeLimits (CSI)\n  - InterPodAffinity\n  - QueueSort\n  - DefaultBinder\n  - DefaultPreemption\n  - SchedulingGates\n\n### 6. Plugin Registry Infrastructure (pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/registry.go)\n\n- `Registry` type (line 71): A map from plugin name strings to PluginFactory functions\n- `PluginFactory` type (line 31): Function signature for creating plugin instances\n\n### Scheduling Cycle Flow\n\n1. `Scheduler.Run()` starts the scheduler main loop\n2. For each pod, `ScheduleOne()` is called:\n   - Retrieves the pod from the queue\n   - Calls PreFilter plugins to initialize state\n   - Calls Filter plugins on each node via `RunFilterPlugins()`\n   - For feasible nodes, calls PreScore and then Score plugins via `RunScorePlugins()`\n   - Selects the best node and enters binding phase\n   - Calls Reserve, PreBind, Bind, PostBind plugins\n3. On failure, PostFilter plugins (like preemption) are called to try to make the pod schedulable\n\nThe `frameworkImpl` runtime manages plugin instances and orchestrates their execution at each extension point, with proper error handling, metrics collection, and support for plugin skipping based on cycle state."
}

